04542nam a22005655i 9780773553774DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735537747 a10.1515/97807735537742doi  a(DE-B1597)655952  a(OCoLC)1034731589  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aPOL0560002bisacsh04a320.971qOCoLC223/eng/202311201 aBrodie, Ian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAt the Centre of Government :bThe Prime Minister and the Limits on Political Power /cIan Brodie. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b6 tables, 5 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tGoverning from the Centre -- tThe Origins of Cabinet Government -- tDelegation and its Limits -- tMaking a Cabinet -- tThe Executive Branch and Parliament -- tManaging a Government Agenda -- tPrime Ministers and Political Parties -- tDemocratizing or Bureaucratizing the Constitution? -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"Canada's prime minister is a dictator." "The Sun King of Canadian government." "More powerful than any other chief executive of any other democratic country." These kinds of claims are frequently made about Canada's leader – especially when the prime minister's party holds a majority government in Parliament. But is there any truth to these arguments? At the Centre of Government not only presents a comprehensively researched work on the structure of political power in Canada but also offers a first-hand view of the inner workings of the Canadian federal government. Ian Brodie – former chief of staff to Prime Minister Stephen Harper and former executive director of the Conservative Party of Canada – argues that the various workings of the Prime Minister's Office, the Privy Council Office, the cabinet, parliamentary committees, and the role of backbench members of Parliament undermine propositions that the prime minister has evolved into the role of an autocrat, with unchecked control over the levers of political power. He corrects the dominant thinking that Canadian prime ministers hold power without limits over their party, caucus, cabinet, Parliament, the public service, and the policy agenda. Citing examples from his time in government and from Canadian political history he argues that in Canada's evolving political system, with its roots in the pre-Confederation era, there are effective checks on executive power, and that the golden age of Parliament and the backbencher is likely now. Drawing on a vast body of work on governance and the role of the executive branch of government, At the Centre of Government is a fact-based primer on the workings of Canadian government and sobering second thoughts about many proposals for reform.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConstitutional lawzCanada. 0aExecutive powerzCanada. 0aFederal governmentzCanada. 0aLegislative powerzCanada. 0aPrime ministerszCanada. 0aSeparation of powerszCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077355377440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773553774423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773553774/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles